            <p>S. MORAIS&#44;<lb/>
                546 N. FIFTH STREET.<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia&#44; Nov. 18 1889<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Cyrus<lb/></p>
            <p>In answer to yours just received&#44; I will<lb/> briefly say&#58;</p>
            <p>1. &#91;Hebrew&#93; Come generally from Africa.  I had one<lb/> made at Tangiers by order of Dr N. S. Mendes&#44; but<lb/> I never used it&#44; because it has a shrill sound.<lb/></p>
            <p>2. The Shofar question is discussed in the &#91;Hebrew&#93; It<lb/> is not unlikely that when the Shofar was blown on<lb/> numerous occasions&#44; one not &#91;Hebrew&#93; may have been<lb/> used.  The &#91;Hebrew&#93; does not mention &#91;Hebrew&#93; in connection with<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; but we learn from the case of &#91;Hebrew&#93; in which<lb/> we read &#91;Hebrew&#93; that the horn must be in both instances<lb/> the same.<lb/></p>
            <p>3. No analogy exists between the &#91;Hebrew&#93; and<lb/> the &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  In the &#91;Hebrew&#93; we find &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> Maimonides&#44; and before him &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; and after<lb/></p>
            
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>him many Sages have given a number of reasons for<lb/> the institution&#44; but I like best the idea of proclaiming<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>4. &#91;Hebrew&#93; is one of the poems&#44; whose author<lb/>&#45;ship is uncertain.  The initials show the name &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> but not having met anywhere with a &#91;Hebrew&#93; of<lb/> that name&#44; I could not say whether the letters are<lb/> intended to tell us the writer.<lb/></p>
            <p>5. &#91;Hebrew&#93; has for its initials &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  The first is an uncommon name&#44; possibly<lb/> Arabic.  The poem is supposed to have been made<lb/> up by three brothers of those names.<lb/></p>
            <p>6. When I saw how the blowing of the Shofar<lb/> destroyed the solemnity of the service because of the<lb/> frequent ineffectual effort of the &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; I asked of<lb/> my friend Dr Isaiah Luzzatto of Padua to procure for<lb/> me one in Italy.  With some difficulty he got it<lb/> from Venice.  It must have been exposed to rats or mice<lb/> that made indentures on it&#44; but not any hole&#44; else<lb/> it would be &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  I enclose a piece of string paper<lb/> showing its dimension and shape.<lb/>  Yours truly<lb/> S Morais<lb/></p>
            </body>
